Partitions, hot keys, and capacity modes.

Under the hood, DynamoDB shards data across many physical partitions, and the partition that holds an item is chosen by hashing the partition key. Two implications fall out of that, and both bite people in production. First, you want high cardinality on the partition key. If millions of items share a handful of partition-key values, like status-equals-active or country-equals-U-S, then almost all reads and writes land on the same physical partition, whose throughput is capped, and the table throttles even when total cluster capacity looks healthy. That's the classic hot-partition failure. The fix is to pick a partition key with many distinct values, or to synthesise one, like status-hash-shard-I-D with a random suffix. Second, you can't query across partitions cheaply. A query operation always targets one partition-key value; if you need items across many partition keys, that points at a global secondary index, the next section.

Capacity modes shape both cost and behaviour. With provisioned capacity, you specify read and write capacity units upfront. One read capacity unit buys one strongly-consistent read per second of an item up to four kilobytes, or two eventually-consistent reads. One write capacity unit buys one write per second up to one kilobyte. Provisioned is cheaper for steady, predictable workloads, but throttles if traffic exceeds the ceiling; Auto Scaling adjusts the provisioned values within a min-max range on a minute scale. With on-demand capacity, there's no planning: DynamoDB scales instantly with traffic and you pay per request. It costs more per request but never throttles on spikes.

The heuristic: use on-demand for new, spiky, or unknown workloads, and provisioned with Auto Scaling for steady, high-volume workloads you can plan.
